| Notes                   = * The film was announced during Marvel Studios' event at El Capitan Theatre on October 28, 2014.<ref name="Announcement">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsarama.com/22570-marvel-studios-event-live.html|title=Marvel Studios Event|work=Newsarama|first=Tom|last=McLean|date=28 October 2014|accessdate=28 October 2014}}</ref>
* Although ''Avengers: Infinity War - Part II'' was the film's original title, the Russo brothers later confirmed that "Part I" and this movie would be re-titled to emphasize the differences between the two films, the former being re-titled to ''[[Avengers: Infinity War]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/russo-brothers-confirm-avengers-infinity-war-title-change/|title=Russo Brothers Confirm: 'Avengers: Infinity War 1 And 2' Will Be Retitled|last=Ryan|first=Mike|work=Uproxx|date=4 May 2016|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref>
* Filming for this film started on August 10, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/TheRussoBrothersOfficial/photos/a.740279982774603.1073741828.739779486157986/1046940722108526/?type=3&theater|title=Beginning the end.|author=The Russo Brothers|work=Facebook|date=10 August 2017|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref> and wrapped on January 11, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://collider.com/avengers-4-wraps-filming-russo-brothers|title= â€˜Avengers 4â€™ Wraps Filming as the Russo Brothers Move into Post-Production|work= Collider|last= Trumbore|first= Dave|date= 2018-01-11|accessdate= 2018-01-12}}</ref> The filmmakers decided to shoot the two ''Avengers'' films back-to-back, despite the previous announcement that it would be shot simultaneously.<ref>{{cite news | first = Joseph| last = Schmidt|  url = http://comicbook.com/marvel/2017/01/22/avengers-infinity-war-sequel-begin-filming/| title = Avengers: Infinity War And Sequel Set To Begin Filming Monday| work = ComicBook.com| date = 2017-01-22| accessdate = 2017-01-24}}</ref>
* The film's title was officially announced as ''Avengers: Endgame'' alongside the debut trailer released on December 7, 2018.<ref>[[:File:Marvel Studios' Avengers - Official Trailer]]</ref>
* This film broke both the domestic opening weekend and worldwide opening box office records, with around $350 million domestic and $1.2 billion worldwide grosses, beating both records previously set by ''Avengers: Infinity War'' ($257.7 million and $640.5 million, respectively).<ref name="Box Office">{{cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2019/04/avengers-endgame-list-of-box-office-records-domestic-china-international-global-milestones-1202603577/|title= â€˜Avengers: Endgameâ€™: Domestic, Overseas & Global Box Office Records â€“ List|work= Deadline|last= Tartaglione|first=  Nancy|date= April 28, 2019|accessdate= April 29, 2019}}</ref>
** Additionally, this film broke the record for the fastest time a film managed to reach $1 billion at the worldwide box office, on its 5th day of release, again beating ''Avengers: Infinity War'' which did so on its 11th day.<ref name="Box Office"/>
* On July 20, 2019, this film surpassed the $2,789.7 billion global gross of ''{{WP|Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar}}'', to become the top grossing film of all time at the worldwide box office (not adjusted for inflation), at the time.{{r|{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/avengers-endgame-passes-avatar-become-no-1-film-all-time-1225121|title=Box Office: 'Avengers: Endgame' Passes 'Avatar' to Become No. 1 Film of All Time|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|date=20 July 2019|accessdate=20 July 2019}}}}
* With a worldwide total box office gross of $2,797 billion, this film became the highest-grossing film of 2019.{{r|{{cite web|url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/year/world/2019/|title= 2019 Worldwide Box Office|work= Box Office Mojo|accessdate= January 5, 2020}}}}
| Trivia                  = * According to co-director [[Anthony Russo]], the argument at the center of this movie was whether one can control their own destiny.<ref name="Slate">{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2019/05/avengers-endgame-ending-twists-directors-interview.html|title=The Directors of Avengers: Endgame on Its Biggest Twists|work=Slate|first=Mike|last=Pesca|date=9 May 2019|accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref>
* Writers {{WP|Christopher Markus}} and {{WP|Stephen McFeely}} contemplated having the disappearance of [[Clinton Barton (Earth-199999)|Hawkeye]]'s family happen at the end of ''[[Avengers: Infinity War]]''.<ref name="NYT">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/29/movies/avengers-endgame-questions-and-answers.html|title=â€˜Avengers: Endgameâ€™: The Screenwriters Answer Every Question You Might Have|work=The New York Times|first=Dave|last=Itzkoff|date=29 April 2019|accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref>
* In certain cuts of the movie, [[Carol Danvers (Earth-199999)|Captain Marvel]] wouldn't be revealed to be responsible of saving [[Anthony Stark (Earth-199999)|Tony Stark]] and [[Nebula (Earth-199999)|Nebula]] until after the ship got back to [[Earth]].<ref name="io9">{{cite web|url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/all-of-the-coolest-trivia-revealed-on-the-avengers-end-1837006830|title=All of the Coolest Trivia Revealed on the Avengers: Endgame Blu-ray|work=Gizmodo|first=Germain|last=Lussier|date=12 August 2019|accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref>
* Markus and McFeely struggled to decide where to take [[Thanos (Earth-199999)|Thanos]]' character from the previous movie. It was Executive Producer Trinh Tran's suggestion to kill him early on.<ref name="NYT"/>
* The five-year time jump was inspired in part by TV series such as ''{{WP|Fargo}}'' and ''{{WP|Lost}}''.<ref name="NYT"/>
* The trajectories of the heroes in the film were determined as sort of a ''[[What If?]]'' scenario.<ref name="NYT"/>
* When brainstorming ideas for each character's arc, it was considered to have Thor on a mission of vengeance. This idea was scrapped since the character's arc in ''Infinity War'' already had consisted of that.<ref name="NYT"/>
* In an early draft of the film, following the 5-year jump, Steve Rogers would've been living with [[Sharon Carter (Earth-199999)|Sharon Carter]], but their relationship would've been turbulent. Carter's role was eventually excised because it was inessential to the plot of the movie.{{r|{{cite web|url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/avengers-endgame-draft-steve-rogers-living-sharon-carter/|title=Avengers: Endgameâ€™s Original Ending Had Steve Rogers Living With Sharon Carter|work=We Got This Covered|first=Christian|last=Bone|date=20 May 2019|accessdate=22 May 2019}}}}
* An idea directors Anthony and [[Joe Russo]] tried to work into the movie was the scenario that roughly a quarter of all children worldwide would've been left orphaned after Thanos' snap. At a point early into development, they worked this angle by having Black Widow lead an organization in [[Washington, D.C.]] that was in charge of orphans.<ref name="Slate"/>
* An idea for the status quo after the 5-year jump was for [[James Rhodes (Earth-199999)|Jim Rhodes]] to have become Vice President of the United States.{{r|{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/marvel/2019/10/24/war-machine-avengers-endgame-president-marvel-series/|title=Avengers: Endgame Had Bigger Plans for War Machine, Still a Possibility|work=ComicBook.com|first=Brandon|last=Davis|date=24 October 2019|accessdate=24 October 2019}}}}
* Scrapped versions of the script showed that memorials like that in [[San Francisco]] existed in every city in the world.<ref name="NYT"/>
* McFeely wrote scenes of Bruce Banner working in a lab to transform himself into "Smart Hulk." Additionally, in an early version of the plot of ''Infinity War'', Banner would have evolved into Smart Hulk during the battle of [[Wakanda]].<ref name="NYT"/> Since this plot resolution was scrapped late into development, certain scenes of the first act of ''Endgame'' had to be reshot, since they originally made use of Smart Hulk.{{r|{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/avengers-endgame-writers-alternate-storylines|title=How the Avengers: Endgame Writers Made Life-and-Death Decisions|work=Vanity Fair|first=Anthony|last=Breznican|date=20 November 2019|accessdate=25 December 2019}}}}
* In Tony's bedtime exchange with Morgan, they originally told each other "I love you tons." The expression "I love you 3,000" is a thing that Tony Stark actor {{WP|Robert Downey Jr.}}'s children have said to him in real life.<ref name="Express">{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/films/1197249/Avengers-Endgame-Tony-Stark-catchphrase-love-you-3000-Robert-Downey-Jr-script-secret|title=Avengers Endgame: 'I love you 3000' secret revealed in HEARTBREAKING Robert Downey Jr move|work=The Express|date=6 November 2019|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>
* The element of time-travel was brought to the table by Producer [[Kevin Feige]], who wanted to use the [[Time Stone]], or use time as an element.<ref name="NYT"/>
* Physicists were consulted for the formulation of the movie's time-travel.<ref name="NYT"/>
* Test screening audiences were confused by the film's rules of time-travel in comparison to ''{{WP|Back to the Future}}'', prompting reshoots of multiple jokes and explanations of the nuances of time-travel, including the scene in which [[Bruce Banner (Earth-199999)|Bruce Banner]] explicitly dismisses time-travel movies listed by Jim Rhodes and [[Scott Lang (Earth-199999)|Scott Lang]], including ''Back to the Future''.{{r|{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/avengers-endgame-russos-mcu-time-travel-rules/|title=Russo Brothers Break Down the MCU's Rules For Time Travel|work=CBR.com|first=Sam|last=Stone|date=2 May 2019|accessdate=3 May 2019}}}}
* The reason Clint's test travel through time is timed is because the Avengers expected that he could want to stay in the past. In a version of the movie's story, Clint attacked the Hulk after being forced to return.<ref name="io9"/>
* A scene cut after Clint's return from the past had Scott Lang offer him orange slices as a callback to ''[[Captain America: Civil War]]''.<ref name="io9"/>
* An unused idea for the movie involved Captain America going to space and travelling the galaxy with the [[Johann Schmidt (Earth-TRN734)|Red Skull]] as an untrustworthy sidekick to track down the errant Infinity Stones.<ref name="VF">{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/07/avengers-endgame-captain-america-head-tony-stark-smart-hulk-thor-sdcc-russos-markus-mcfeely|title=Avengers: Endgame Filmmakers Reveal Dark, Trippy Original Version at Comic-Con|work=Fanity Fair|first=Joanna|last=Robinson|date=19 July 2019|accessdate=20July 2019}}</ref>
* Markus and McFeely initially avoided having the characters time-travel to the Battle of New York since they considered it "pander-y" until co-Director Joe Russo asked for it. In the first draft of the film, the Avengers would have tried to get the [[Cosmic Cube|Tesseract]] from [[Asgard (City)|Asgard]] since the artifact was there at one point with the [[Reality Stone|Aether]]. In this version of the film, Iron Man would have infiltrated Asgard using a [[Stealth Armor|stealth armor]], but he would have had to fight [[Heimdall]] whose abilities would allow him to detect Stark. In this early draft, Thor would have had long scenes with [[Jane Foster]], and the Avengers would've tried to retrieve the [[Power Stone]] from [[Morag]] when the planet was still flooded.<ref name="NYT"/>
* In a version of the story in which [[Wanda Maximoff (Earth-199999)|Scarlet Witch]] was one of the surviving heroes, she and [[Rocket Raccoon (Earth-199999)|Rocket]] went to the [[Triskelion (New York City)|Triskelion]] to get the [[Cosmic Cube|Tesseract]], and would then take a ride to the [[Sanctum Sanctorum]] and use its portal into the [[Kamar-Taj]] to get the [[Time Stone]].{{r|{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/marvel/2019/07/27/avengers-endgame-cut-scarlet-witch-rocket-road-trip-plot/|title=Avengers: Endgame Writers Reveal Cut Scarlet Witch and Rocket Raccoon Road Trip|work=ComicBook.com|first=JK|last=Schmidt|date=27 July 2019|accessdate=27 July 2019}}}}<ref name="NYT"/>
* The moment in which the Avengers arrive from the future to the Battle of New York was changed in post-production. An early version had the team arrive after Iron Man kills a [[Leviathans (Chitauri)|Leviathan]] by flying through it and blowing it up from the inside. Test audienced required several minutes to acclimate themselves. Another version had the entry point be when the [[Bruce Banner (Earth-199999)|Hulk]] beats up [[Loki Laufeyson (Earth-199999)|Loki]] like a ragdoll.<ref name="Insider">{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/inside-the-editing-process-of-avengers-endgame-black-widow-scene-change-2019-5|title=Inside the editing of 'Avengers: Endgame,' which included drastic changes to Black Widow's big moment and the time-travel scenes|work=Business Insider|first=Jason|last=Guerrasio|date=13 May 2019|accessdate=27 May 2019}}</ref>
* The moment when Hulk imitates his old self in 2012 New York wasn't originally in the movie. Animators did it as a joke, but the Russos liked it and had {{WP|Mark Ruffalo}} recreate it with motion capture.<ref name="io9"/>
* The color scheme of the [[Iron Man Armor MK LXXXV (Earth-199999)|Iron Man Armor MK LXXXV]], namely the pronounced use of gold in the arms and legs, was chosen to be reminiscent of the [[Iron Man Armor Model 4|Classic Iron Man Armor]] from the comics.<ref name="Meinderding">{{cite web|url=https://screencrush.com/ryan-meinerding-marvel-concept-art-interview/|title=Ryan Meinerding, Marvelâ€™s Head of Visual Development, Takes Us Behind-the-Scenes of Designing the MCU|work=Screen Crush|first=Matt|last=Singer|date=25 July 2019|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>
* There were versions of the movie written with [[Nick Fury]] and another with [[Maria Hill]] appointed to retrieve [[Loki's Scepter]] from the Avengers. After [[Alexander Pierce (Earth-199999)|Alexander Pierce]] actor {{WP|Robert Redford}} announced he was going to retire from acting, Markus and McFeely considered asking him to reprise his role.<ref name="NYT"/>
* The shots from Asgard of [[Loki Laufeyson (Earth-TRN733)|Loki]] and [[Jane Foster (Earth-TRN733)|Jane Foster]] were repurposed from unused ''[[Thor: The Dark World]]'' footage. Because of this, {{WP|Natalie Portman}} didn't have to step on set once to be in the film.<ref name="Insider"/>
* A scene scrapped from the film's script had Rocket uncomfortably explain to Jane Foster why and how he had to remove the Aether from her body.<ref name="VF"/>
* Scenes with past Nebula were reshot to better explain her having two frequencies of consciousness.<ref name="io9"/>
* [[Howard Stark (Earth-TRN735)|Howard Stark]] getting sauerkraut for his wife was inspired by Stephen McFeely's mother craving sauerkraut when she was pregnant with him.<ref name="io9"/>
* [[Margaret Carter (Earth-TRN735)|Peggy Carter]] was not going to appear in the 1974 sequence in the first draft of the script.<ref name="io9"/>
* Drafts of the movie were written with Hawkeye making the sacrifice for the [[Soul Stone]].<ref name="Empire">{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/avengers-endgame-26-spoilers-explained-directors-writers/|title=Avengers Endgame: 26 Spoilers Explained By The Directors And Writers|work=Empire|first=Ben|last=Travis|date=7 June 2019|accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref>
* Black Widow's sacrifice was originally shot differently. Clint and Natasha would have been followed to [[Vormir]] by [[Thanos (Earth-TRN734)|Thanos]] and his army and a small battle ensued. During the fight, Natasha decides to run off the cliff, and Clint tries to stop her while also fending off the attack. Despite test audiences reacting to the scene positively, it was reshot and changed to the final version to make something that serviced Black Widow more.<ref name="Insider"/>
* The design lines of Hulk's jumpsuit are meant to form a big "H" on his chest.<ref name="Meinderding"/>
* An early draft saw all the fallen heroes reunite at the Avengers Facility before Thanos attacks.<ref name="Empire"/>
* The Russo Brothers dubbed Thanos' younger self as "Warrior Thanos," since he was more precocious and self-confident and "not quite as enlightened," whereas the Thanos from ''Avengers: Infinity War'' was mellowed-out and philosophical.<ref name="Empire"/>
* An idea left unused for the opening of the final battle was that the Thanos from 2014 would have gone to Earth and killed the Avengers of his era, bringing the decapitated head of that timeline's Captain America to taunt the future Avengers.<ref name="VF"/>
* A longer version of the film's final battle was written and shot. This climax was going to have its own three-act structure.<ref name="NYT"/>
*The [[Avengers (Earth-199999)|Avengers]] entering the Quantum Realm and the Time Hiest scenes are similar to how the [[Avengers (Earth-12041)|Avengers]] entering and saving Avengers who were struck in multiple realites by the [[Cabal (Earth-12041)|Cabal]] in the ''[[Marvel's Avengers Assemble|Marvel's Avengers: Secret Wars]]'' episode "[[Marvel's Avengers Assemble Season 4 8|The Once and Future Kang]]."{{r|Marvel's Avengers Assemble Season 4 8}}
* Hulk holding the rubble of the Avengers Facility is a reference to {{cl|Marvel Super Heroes Secret Wars Vol 1 4}}, in which the [[Bruce Banner (Earth-616)|Hulk]] holds a mountain to stop it from crushing the heroes of the story.<ref name="Empire"/>
* A scrapped scene written for the final battle consisted of a moment in a trench where the battle had gotten paused for roughly three minutes and approximately eighteen characters were going to discuss strategies in a way Markus and McFeely eventually regarded didn't flow like a natural conversation and felt "completely fake" and "fraudulent."<ref name="NYT"/>
* [[Henry Pym (Earth-199999)|Hank Pym]] and [[Janet Van Dyne (Earth-199999)|Janet Van Dyne]] were considered to appear in the final battle since they had their own Ant-Man and Wasp suits.<ref name="NYT"/>
* There was a scene envisioned for the final act in which the [[James Barnes (Earth-199999)|Winter Soldier]] would have saved Iron Man and [[Virginia Potts (Earth-199999)|Rescue]] in the battlefield. Bucky and Tony would then have had a moment in which Stark forgives him for the death of his parents, or at least have acknowledged that it wasn't his fault.{{r|{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/marvel-cinematic-universe-christopher-markus-stephen-mcfeely-interview/|title=Christopher Markus & Stephen McFeely Interview: MCU|work=ScreenRant|date=5 November 2020|accessdate=28 February 2020}}}}
* In an earlier draft of the movie, 2014's [[Nebula (Earth-TRN734)|Nebula]] would have intercepted Stark's Infinity Gauntlet during the final battle. She would have tried to use the glove herself in an attempt to prove herself to Thanos but would have died. This scene would also have doubled as a nod to {{cl|Infinity Gauntlet Vol 1 5}}, in which [[Nebula (Earth-616)|Nebula]] wields the Infinity Gauntlet.{{r|{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/avengers-endgame-nebula-infinity-gauntlet-concept-art/|title=Nebula Nearly Wore the Infinity Gauntlet in Avengers: Endgame|work=CBR.com|first=Anthony|last=Gramuglia|date=20 November 2019|accessdate=20 November 2019}}}}
* Directors {{WP|Russo brothers|Anthony and Joe Russo}} sought Robert Downey Jr.'s approval for his character's arc in the film. Downey had mixed emotions about it, but ultimately approved it.{{r|{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/robert-downey-jr-had-mixed-emotions-avengers-endgame-ending-1206174|title='Avengers: Endgame' Directors on Seeking Robert Downey Jr.'s Blessing and Marvel's First Gay Character|work=Hollywood Reporter|first=Aaron|last=Couch|date=1 May 2019|accessdate=3 May 2019}}}}
* Various versions of the final confrontation between Thanos and Iron Man were shot; some featured lines of dialogue, others had Robert Downey Jr. improvise, and before the scene was reshot, the scene was silent. It was eventually decided that Thanos needed a moment at the end of the movie where he says something. It was decided to have him echo the final words of his future self to create symmetry.<ref name="Insider"/>
* Editor Jeff Ford came up with the idea of Tony's "I am Iron Man" retort. Robert Downey Jr. was initially reluctant to reshoot the scene and get into the emotional state required for it. Producer Joel Silver helped convince Downey to do it.{{r|{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2471343/apparently-robert-downey-jr-didnt-want-to-do-tony-starks-last-big-line-in-avengers-endgame|title=Apparently Robert Downey Jr. Didnâ€™t Want To Do Tony Starkâ€™s Last Big Line In Avengers: Endgame|work=CinemaBlend|first=Sean|last=O'Connell|date=6 May 2019|accessdate=27 May 2019}}}}
* {{WP|Katherine Langford}} was cast as a grown-up version of Morgan Stark, whom Tony would see in a vision after snapping his fingers, mirroring a similar moment between Thanos and a vision of Gamora in ''Avengers: Infinity War''. According to the Russo Brothers, test audiences were confused by the scene, and it was ultimately cut because there was no emotional association with the adult version of Tony's daughter. The main idea behind the scene was to have future Morgan forgive Tony and give him peace before his death. Joe Russo explained that while the idea felt resonate, the movie was already over complicated.{{r|{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/katherine-langford-was-cut-avengers-endgame-as-tony-starks-daughter-1207787|title=Why Katherine Langford's 'Avengers: Endgame' Scene Was Cut|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Aaron|last=Couch|date=6 May 2019|accessdate=31 May 2019}}}}
* Tony's death scene was shot without a script. Instead, Robert Downey Jr., {{WP|Tom Holland}}, {{WP|Gwyneth Paltrow}} and {{WP|Don Cheadle}} were only told the context of the scene and given a few directions, the rest was improvised.{{r|{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jBY4vKXT_Ss|title=Tom Holland: Iron Man death sequence was UNSCRIPTED I Spider-Man: Far From Home|work=PinkvillaINKVILLA|date=14 June 2019|accessdate=14 June 2019}}}}
* Markus and McFeely wrote a number of dying words for Tony Stark, but Robert Downey Jr. thought it would be much more powerful for Tony to die silently.<ref name="VF"/>
* Past Thanos sitting on a rock waiting to die was meant to mirror the character's future self sitting on his porch at the end of ''Infinity War''.<ref name="io9"/>
* A scrapped extended version of Tony's death scene had the heroes bending on their knee to honor Stark's sacrifice. The scene additionally showed [[Gamora (Earth-TRN734)|Gamora]] slipping away while the heroes were mourning. The scene was filmed prior to Tony Stark's funeral, which the Russo Brothers felt was a more resonant and emotional reflection on Tony's.{{r|{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/movies/2019/07/26/endgame-avengers-salute-their-fallen-exclusive-deleted-scene/1827992001/|title=See how the Avengers honor a fallen superhero in exclusive 'Endgame' deleted scene|work=USA Today|first=Brian|last=Truitt|date=26 July 2019|accessdate=26 July 2019}}}}
* Tony Stark saying "I love you 3,000" at the end of his speech was included during additional dialogue recording, which is why it's delivered off-screen.<ref name="io9"/>
* Natasha Romanoff didn't get a funeral because she was a cipher and Markus and McFeely didn't feel it was honest to the character to give her a funeral.<ref name="NYT"/>
* According to Markus and McFeely, Tony Stark and [[Steven Rogers (Earth-199999)|Steve Rogers]]' finales mirror each other's story arc; Tony was about moving to selflessness while Steve moved towards self-interest.<ref name="NYT"/>
* The idea for showing the main cast's signatures in the final credits was inspired by the end credits of ''{{Wc|memory-alpha:Star Trek VI| The Undiscovered Country|Star Trek VI: The Undiscovered Country}}''.<ref name="io9"/>
* Kevin Feige had the idea to end the movie with an audio callback to ''[[Iron Man (film)|Iron Man]]'' to accompany the Marvel Studios logo. The production team dug through the material of ''Iron Man'' and found the smithing sounds used in the movie when Tony Stark was building the [[Iron Man Armor MK I (Earth-199999)|Iron Man Armor MK I]]. The sound's rhythm was adjusted slightly for its reuse.<ref name="Insider"/>
* This is the last Marvel Cinematic Universe film with a cameo appearance from [[Stan Lee]].
* In a non-canon commercial for {{sl|The Falcon and The Winter Soldier}}, the identity of "Noobmaster69" was jokingly revealed to be Aaron from {{sl|Captain America: The Winter Soldier}}.{{r|{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Xbox/status/1371491381395353601?s=20|title=You donâ€™t need a Vibranium shield to be a hero. Admittedly, it does help.|work=Twitter|author=Xbox|date=15 March 2021|accessdate=16 March 2021}}}}

